How @Transactional Works Internally (REAL AOP):
  High-Level Flow:
      Client
        ↓
      Proxy (TransactionInterceptor)
        ↓
      Start Transaction
        ↓
      Business Method
        ↓
      Commit / Rollback
🔹 Step-by-Step Internal Working:
      Step 1: Annotation Detection - Spring scans:
            @Transactional
            public void transfer() {}
      Step 2: Proxy Creation - Spring wraps bean with proxy containing:  TransactionInterceptor
      Step 3: Method Call Intercepted-   When method is called:  proxy.transfer()
      Step 4: Transaction Starts-  Internally: transactionManager.begin();
      Step 5: Execute Business Logic -  target.transfer();
      Step 6: Commit or Rollback
              if (success) {
                  commit();
              } else {
                  rollback();
              }
Real Internal Classes (Advanced):
      TransactionInterceptor
      PlatformTransactionManager
      TransactionAspectSupport
Simplified Internal Code:
      public Object invoke(MethodInvocation invocation) throws Throwable {
          TransactionStatus status = txManager.getTransaction();
          try {
              Object result = invocation.proceed(); // actual method
              txManager.commit(status);
              return result;
          } catch (Exception e) {
              txManager.rollback(status);
              throw e;
          }
      }

