self-invocation problem:
    The self-invocation problem is a common pitfall in Spring applications. 
    It occurs when a method within a class calls another method in the same class that is annotated
    with a proxy-based annotation like @Transactional, @Retryable, @Async, or @Cacheable.
    
    Even though the annotation is present, it will not work (the transaction won't start, or the retry logic won't trigger).
    Why it occurs: The Proxy Pattern
        To understand why it fails, you have to look at how Spring applies these features.
        Spring doesn't actually modify your original code. 
        Instead, it creates a Proxy (a "wrapper" object) around your bean.
    Normal Call (External): When a different class (e.g., a Controller) calls your Service, it calls the Proxy.
                            The Proxy starts the transaction or retry logic and then calls your actual method.
    Self-Invocation (Internal): When Method A calls Method B inside the same class, it uses the this reference. 
                                This bypasses the Proxy entirely and goes straight to the local method.
Scenario 1: @Transactional
    @Service
    public class PaymentService {
    
        public void processOrder() {
            // External call comes here... then:
            savePayment(); // SELF-INVOCATION!
        }
    
        @Transactional
        public void savePayment() {
            // This transaction will NOT start
            // Database changes won't roll back if an error occurs
        }
    }
    Result: If processOrder() is not transactional itself, calling savePayment() directly will execute the SQL without a transaction.
            If an exception happens, no rollback occurs.

Scenario 2: @Retryable
      @Service
      public class StockService {
      
          public void checkStock() {
              updateInventory(); // SELF-INVOCATION!
          }
      
          @Retryable(retryFor = RuntimeException.class)
          public void updateInventory() {
              // This will NOT retry on failure
              throw new RuntimeException("Network fail");
          }
      }
      Result: The updateInventory() method will throw the exception once and stop. 
              The Spring Retry logic is never triggered because the Proxy interceptor was skipped.

How to Fix It
1. Move the Method (Best Practice)
    The cleanest way to fix this is to move the annotated method to a separate service. 
    This ensures that every call goes through the Spring Proxy.
      Instead of: ServiceA.methodA -> ServiceA.methodB
      Do: ServiceA.methodA -> ServiceB.methodB

2. Self-Injection (The "Workaround")
    You can inject a bean of the same class into itself.
    This forces the call to go through the proxy.

    @Service
    public class MyService {
        @Autowired
        private MyService self; // Injecting the proxy version of itself
    
        public void outerMethod() {
            self.annotatedMethod(); // Now it goes through the proxy!
        }
    
        @Transactional
        public void annotatedMethod() { ... }
    }
3. Use AspectJ (Advanced)
      If you switch from Spring AOP (proxy-based) to AspectJ, the logic is woven directly into the bytecode.
      This solves self-invocation because the "intercept" happens inside the method itself, but it requires more complex build-time configuration.

4. Programmatic Approach
      Instead of using annotations, you can use TransactionTemplate or RetryTemplate inside your code.
      This doesn't rely on proxies and works perfectly with internal calls.
      
